{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638579"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17722"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116752"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10436"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10168"},{"type":"tags","id":"10320"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24482"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116752"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMechanoreceptors in human skin are specialised to detect different types of mechanical stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of Ruffini corpuscles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sense temperature changes","Detect sustained skin stretch","Respond to hair movement","Detect rapid vibrations","Respond to light touch"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERuffini corpuscles are slow-adapting mechanoreceptors located in the deep dermis that \u003Cstrong\u003Edetect sustained skin stretch\u003C/strong\u003E. They continue to fire action potentials throughout prolonged mechanical stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESense temperature changes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this is mediated by specialised thermoreceptors, not mechanoreceptors. \u003Cstrong\u003ERespond to hair movement\u003C/strong\u003E is detected by hair follicle receptors. \u003Cstrong\u003EDetect rapid vibrations\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of Pacinian corpuscles, which detect pressure changes. \u003Cstrong\u003ERespond to light touch\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the responsibility of Meissner\u0027s corpuscles in the superficial dermis of glabrous skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe slow-adapting nature of Ruffini corpuscles makes them particularly important for detecting and maintaining awareness of sustained mechanical deformation of the skin and joint capsules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ruffini corpuscles are slow-adapting mechanoreceptors found in the deep layers of skin that detect skin stretch.","Ruffini corpuscles are particularly abundant in the dermis of hairy skin and joint capsules.","As slow-adapting receptors, Ruffini corpuscles continue to fire throughout sustained mechanical stimulation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition, 2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 48; pg. 608."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]}